{"title_page": "Coadjutor bishop", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Catholic Church Hierarchy}}\n\nA '''coadjutor bishop''' (or '''bishop coadjutor''') is a bishop in the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Anglican Communion|Anglican]], and (historically) [[Eastern Orthodox]] churches whose main role is to assist the [[diocesan bishop]] in the administration of the diocese.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O4pj9YNdgJYC&pg=PA91&lpg=PA91&dq=coadjutor+orthodox&source=bl&ots=sRX0COWlpq&sig=ZXzkGIr6ptAn3jRQMTTiT7eLFoM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIvdvry-_SAhUNxmMKHSElBD8Q6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&q=coadjutor%20orthodox&f=false|title=The Sabaite Heritage in the Orthodox Church from the Fifth Century to the Present|last=Patrich|first=Joseph|date=2001|publisher=Peeters Publishers|year=|isbn=9789042909762|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yp6oDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT184&lpg=PT184&dq=coadjutor+orthodox&source=bl&ots=788TgjrIQs&sig=FmFLnOkU5l9jiYbXBJvt3MZ_M7A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIvdvry-_SAhUNxmMKHSElBD8Q6AEIODAI#v=onepage&q=coadjutor%20orthodox&f=false|title=The Latin Church in the Crusader States: The Secular Church|last=Hamilton|first=Bernard|date=2016-12-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351887052|language=en}}</ref> The coadjutor (literally, \"co-assister\" in Latin) is a bishop himself, although he is also appointed as [[vicar general]]. The coadjutor bishop is, however, given authority beyond that ordinarily given to the vicar general, making him co-head of the diocese in all but ceremonial precedence. In modern times, the coadjutor automatically succeeds the diocesan bishop upon the latter's retirement, removal, or death.\n\n==Roman Catholic Church==\n{{main|Bishop (Catholic Church)}}\nIn the [[Roman Catholic Church]], a coadjutor bishop is an immediate collaborator of the diocesan bishop, similar to an [[auxiliary bishop]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Canon 403 \u00a73 |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana |work=1983 [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|Code of Canon Law]] |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115203240/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |archivedate=15 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Canon 403 \u00a71 |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana |work=1983 [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|Code of Canon Law]] |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115203240/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |archivedate=15 January 2010 }}</ref> However, unlike auxiliary bishops, coadjutors are given the right of succession to the [[episcopal see]]. When the diocesan bishop dies, retires, resigns, or is reassigned, the coadjutor automatically becomes the next bishop of the [[Particular Church|local Church]] ([[diocese]]). Until then, the diocesan bishop appoints the coadjutor to act as [[vicar general]]. He needs to be a bishop, and, in a now-discontinued practice, held a [[titular see]] until his succession.\n\nIn modern church practice, the appointment of a coadjutor is usually done in cases where a diocesan bishop feels that he will not be able to continue in his position for health reasons or impending retirement. In such cases, the Pope may assign a coadjutor in order to give him time to become familiar with the diocese that he will eventually take over. For example, Bishop [[Dennis Marion Schnurr]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Duluth|Diocese of Duluth]], [[Minnesota]], was named Coadjutor Archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cincinnati|Archdiocese of Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], in 2008 to succeed aging Archbishop [[Daniel Edward Pilarczyk]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAt times, the appointment of a coadjutor is used to discreetly remove a diocesan bishop who has become involved in scandal or other problems. An example of this occurred in the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque|Archdiocese of Dubuque]] in the 1940s, when Archbishop [[Francis Beckman]] involved the archdiocese in what turned out to be a dubious mining scheme. When the scheme fell apart and resulted in serious financial problems for Beckman and the archdiocese, Bishop [[Henry Rohlman]], of [[Davenport, Iowa]], was appointed Coadjutor Archbishop of Dubuque. While Beckman was allowed to retain the office of Archbishop, it was made clear to him by the [[Holy See]] that the actual power rested with Rohlman.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nPrior to the reform of the [[Code of Canon Law]] in 1983, a distinction was made between coadjutor bishops ''cum jure succesionis'' (\"with the right of succession\") and those without. Some coadjutors were appointed with the right of succession, and others were without such a right, usually in archbishops with particularly large dioceses who also held other important posts and to honor certain auxiliary bishops).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nFor an example of a coadjutor without right of succession, see [[John Maguire (coadjutor archbishop of New York)|John J. Maguire]], coadjutor archbishop of New York (1965-1980).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Now, every coadjutor who is appointed has the concomitant right of succession.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAn [[Apostolic Vicar]] may also have a coadjutor, who, like him, will be a [[titular bishop]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Anglican Communion==\nIn some [[province (Anglican)|provinces]] of the [[Anglican Communion]], a bishop coadjutor (the form usually used) is a bishop elected or appointed to follow the current diocesan bishop upon the incumbent's death or retirement. For example, in the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]], when a diocesan bishop announces a retirement, a special diocesan convention is held to elect a coadjutor. Usually, the coadjutor serves with the incumbent for a short time before the latter's retirement, when the coadjutor becomes the diocesan bishop. Bishops coadjutor are also appointed in the [[Reformed Episcopal Church]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe role of \"assistant bishop\" (with no expectation to succeed the diocesan see) in the [[Church of England]] is fulfilled by a [[suffragan bishop|suffragan]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThere have been bishops coadjutor in the [[Anglican Church of Australia]] without the right of succession to the diocesan see.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Catholicism |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coadjutor Bishop}}\n[[Category:Bishops by type]]\n[[Category:Catholic ecclesiastical titles]]\n[[Category:Ecclesiastical titles]]\n[[Category:Episcopacy in the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:Anglican episcopal offices]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=March 2017}}\n\n{{Catholic Church Hierarchy}}\n\nA '''coadjutor bishop''' (or '''bishop coadjutor''') is a bishop in the [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Anglican Communion|Anglican]], and (historically) [[Eastern Orthodox]] churches whose main role is to assist the [[diocesan bishop]] in the administration of the diocese.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O4pj9YNdgJYC&pg=PA91&lpg=PA91&dq=coadjutor+orthodox&source=bl&ots=sRX0COWlpq&sig=ZXzkGIr6ptAn3jRQMTTiT7eLFoM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIvdvry-_SAhUNxmMKHSElBD8Q6AEIIzAB#v=onepage&q=coadjutor%20orthodox&f=false|title=The Sabaite Heritage in the Orthodox Church from the Fifth Century to the Present|last=Patrich|first=Joseph|date=2001|publisher=Peeters Publishers|year=|isbn=9789042909762|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yp6oDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT184&lpg=PT184&dq=coadjutor+orthodox&source=bl&ots=788TgjrIQs&sig=FmFLnOkU5l9jiYbXBJvt3MZ_M7A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIvdvry-_SAhUNxmMKHSElBD8Q6AEIODAI#v=onepage&q=coadjutor%20orthodox&f=false|title=The Latin Church in the Crusader States: The Secular Church|last=Hamilton|first=Bernard|date=2016-12-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351887052|language=en}}</ref> The coadjutor (literally, \"co-assister\" in Latin) is a bishop himself, although he is also appointed as [[vicar general]]. The coadjutor bishop is, however, given authority beyond that ordinarily given to the vicar general, making him co-head of the diocese in all but ceremonial precedence. In modern times, the coadjutor automatically succeeds the diocesan bishop upon the latter's retirement, removal, or death.\n\n==Roman Catholic Church==\n{{main|Bishop (Catholic Church)}}\nIn the [[Roman Catholic Church]], a coadjutor bishop is an immediate collaborator of the diocesan bishop, similar to an [[auxiliary bishop]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Canon 403 \u00a73 |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana |work=1983 [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|Code of Canon Law]] |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115203240/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |archivedate=15 January 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Canon 403 \u00a71 |url=https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana |work=1983 [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|Code of Canon Law]] |accessdate=6 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100115203240/https://www.vatican.va/archive/ENG1104/__P1F.HTM |archivedate=15 January 2010 }}</ref> However, unlike auxiliary bishops, coadjutors are given the right of succession to the [[episcopal see]]. When the diocesan bishop dies, retires, resigns, or is reassigned, the coadjutor automatically becomes the next bishop of the [[Particular Church|local Church]] ([[diocese]]). Until then, the diocesan bishop appoints the coadjutor to act as [[vicar general]]. He needs to be a bishop, and, in a now-discontinued practice, held a [[titular see]] until his succession.\n\nIn modern church practice, the appointment of a coadjutor is usually done in cases where a diocesan bishop feels that he will not be able to continue in his position for health reasons or impending retirement. In such cases, the Pope may assign a coadjutor in order to give him time to become familiar with the diocese that he will eventually take over. For example, Bishop [[Dennis Marion Schnurr]] of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Duluth|Diocese of Duluth]], [[Minnesota]], was named Coadjutor Archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cincinnati|Archdiocese of Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], in 2008 to succeed aging Archbishop [[Daniel Edward Pilarczyk]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAt times, the appointment of a coadjutor is used to discreetly remove a diocesan bishop who has become involved in scandal or other problems. An example of this occurred in the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque|Archdiocese of Dubuque]] in the 1940s, when Archbishop [[Francis Beckman]] involved the archdiocese in what turned out to be a dubious mining scheme. When the scheme fell apart and resulted in serious financial problems for Beckman and the archdiocese, Bishop [[Henry Rohlman]], of [[Davenport, Iowa]], was appointed Coadjutor Archbishop of Dubuque. While Beckman was allowed to retain the office of Archbishop, it was made clear to him by the [[Holy See]] that the actual power rested with Rohlman.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nPrior to the reform of the [[Code of Canon Law]] in 1983, a distinction was made between coadjutor bishops ''cum jure succesionis'' (\"with the right of succession\") and those without. Some coadjutors were appointed with the right of succession, and others were without such a right, usually in archbishops with particularly large dioceses who also held other important posts and to honor certain auxiliary bishops).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nFor an example of a coadjutor without right of succession, see [[John Maguire (coadjutor archbishop of New York)|John J. Maguire]], coadjutor archbishop of New York (1965-1980).{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} Now, every coadjutor who is appointed has the concomitant right of succession.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nAn [[Apostolic Vicar]] may also have a coadjutor, who, like him, will be a [[titular bishop]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Anglican Communion==\nIn some [[province (Anglican)|provinces]] of the [[Anglican Communion]], a bishop coadjutor (the form usually used) is a bishop elected or appointed to follow the current diocesan bishop upon the incumbent's death or retirement. For example, in the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America]], when a diocesan bishop announces a retirement, a special diocesan convention is held to elect a coadjutor. Usually, the coadjutor serves with the incumbent for a short time before the latter's retirement, when the coadjutor becomes the diocesan bishop. Bishops coadjutor are also appointed in the [[Reformed Episcopal Church]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe role of 'assistant-bishop' (with no expectation to succeed the diocesan see) in the [[Church of England]] is fulfilled by a [[suffragan bishop|suffragan]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThere have been bishops coadjutor in the [[Anglican Church of Australia]] without the right of succession to the diocesan see.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Catholicism |state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coadjutor Bishop}}\n[[Category:Bishops by type]]\n[[Category:Catholic ecclesiastical titles]]\n[[Category:Ecclesiastical titles]]\n[[Category:Episcopacy in the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:Anglican episcopal offices]]\n", "name_user": "Esrever", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnglican Communion:minor cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coadjutor_bishop"}
